Eastern Europe Day-Ahead Power Rises, Tracking German Contract

-- B y   M a r e k   S t r z e l e c k i
-- 
2011-05-17T13:18:59Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-17/eastern-europe-day-ahead-power-rises-tracking-german-contract.html
Day-ahead electricity in eastern
 Europe  advanced as higher German prices boosted exports from the
Czech Republic and  Poland .  Czech day-ahead power rose 9.1 percent to 65.21 euros
($92.34) a megawatt-hour, as the equivalent contract in  Germany ,
a benchmark for eastern Europe, jumped 11 percent to 65.75 euros
a megawatt-hour, according to broker data compiled by Bloomberg.  Polish electricity for tomorrow gained 1.1 percent to
217.65 zloty ($78.43) a megawatt-hour, according to Polish power
exchange data compiled by Bloomberg.  Hungarian electricity, traded on the Budapest-based power
exchange, rose 14 percent to 64.18 euros, according to the
bourse’s website.  The Czech Republic has 17,625 megawatts of capacity
installed, according to Bloomberg data. The country exported
1,909 megawatts of power from 12 p.m. to 1 p.m. local time
today, according to  Entsoe , the European Transmission System
Operators transparency platform. Poland exported 878 megawatts,
mainly to the  Czech Republic  and Germany, at the same time,
according to the data.  Bloomberg tracks power prices from brokers including GFI
Group Inc., ICAP Plc, Spectron Group Ltd., Tradition Financial
Services and Tullett Prebon Plc. Brokers handle the majority of
trading in Europe’s electricity markets.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Marek Strzelecki in Warsaw at 
 mstrzelecki1@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Steve Voss at   sev@bloomberg.net  